photo.title: Bookplate of Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956)
photo.description: Bookplate of Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) received his Ph.D. in psychology from the University of Pennsylvania in 1912 and was a member of the faculty at Clark University from 1912 until his death. F. W. Irwin wrote in Fernberger's obituary in The American Journal of Psychology, Vol. 69.4 (1956), p. 677-678: "At all stages of his career he exhibited an interest in those applications of experimental psychology that employed rigorous, preferably psychophysical, methods. He once testified before the Public Service Commission of Pennsylvania as an expert for the complainant in an action brought by the Yellow Cab Company of Philadelphia to prevent the use by others of taxicabs with colors alleged to resemble too closely the color of Yellow Cabs. His testimony involved not only verbal opinions but also the performance of demonstrations in the hearing room in the presence of the examiner and the interested parties. He mixed colors on a rotary color mixer to match the colors of the complainant's and respondent's cabs, showed that they were closely similar -- they differed by not more than three just noticeable differences along the base of a model of the color solid that was also produced -- and that their resemblance increased as the illumination of the room was decreased." Shortly before his death Fernberger donated a collection of psychological books and journals to the University of Pennsylvania as the Samuel W. Fernberger Collection of Psychology. Established heading: Fernberger, Samuel Weiller, 1887-1956 Other examples of Samuel Weiller Fernberger provenance Penn Libraries call numbers: GrC T3428 Ef9 1549 LatC C4855.2 1546 All images from this book EC85 Al612 905f

photo.title: Bookplate of George Dunn (1864-1912), English bibliographer and book collector
photo.description: Bookplate of George Dunn (1864-1912), English bibliographer and book collector. From his obituary: On Tuesday of last week there died suddenly from pneumonia, at the age of forty-seven, a man whose remarkable gifts and attainments deserve more than the few paragraphs of record that have appeared in the public press. Mr. George Dunn, of Woolley Hall, near Maidenhead, was a member of a well-known Northumbrian Catholic family. He was educated at Beaumont College, Windsor, and at Stonyhurst, and was afterwards called to the Bar, though he never practised as a barrister. Inheriting from his father, the late George Dunn, of Bath House, Newcastle, large estates both in Northumberland and Berkshire, together with sufficient revenues, he was able to indulge the tastes of a scholar and collector of early printed books, mediaeval bindings, manuscripts, old silver, and old clocks, as well as those of a sportsman and keen angler, an astronomer and a student of forestry. Of none of these things was he content to have a superficial knowledge. Indeed, it may be said that he handled nothing without mastering it completely ... With these and other interests and pursuits George Dunn lived a tranquil and sequestered life, unmarried and alone in a large house, where he occasionally entertained one or other of the small band of intimates to whom he was devoted and by whom he was beloved. Neatly dressed, shy, spare, and rather below the middle height, he might sometimes be seen entering the British Museum or the Bodleian Library, or quietly turning over the book-treasures in the London sale rooms. But he never attended meetings or went into society, or gave the smallest encouragement to mere acquaintances. He was a Conservative in politics, a model landlord, and a loyal son of the Catholic Church. -- "Mr. George Dunn," The Times (11 March 1912), p. 11, issue 39843, col C. Established heading: Dunn, George, 1864-1912 Penn Libraries call number: GrC Ar694.4 1535

photo.title: Thomas Randall (1805-1887)
photo.description: Thomas Randall High St. Oxford Perhaps Thomas Randall (1805-1887), whose shop was located at 22 High Street, according to Stephanie Jenkins's website on Oxford history. Randall attended New College School in Oxford as a child before going into the family business as a mercer and hatter. He was elected Mayor of Oxford for 1859-1860 and alderman in 1861, from which post he retired in 1886. A contemporary account describes him as "jolly Tom Randall, mercer, alderman, scholar." photo.title: Bookplate of Gaspard Ernest Stroehlin (1844-1907)
photo.description: Bookplate of Gaspard Ernest Stroehlin (1844-1907), a Swiss minister and professor (specializing in church history) at the University of Geneva. "Mente libera" was his motto; "Champel" appears to be an allusion to Champel, Switzerland, where the reformer Michael Servetus was burned at the stake in 1553. The building in the background is probably St. Pierre Cathedral in Geneva, where Calvin famously preached. Hans Asper bound several of Stroehlin's books; cf. I. Krekler, Stammbücher bis 1625 (Wiesbaden: Harassowitz, 1999), p. 6 (nr. 2). Established as Stroehlin, Ernest, 1844-1907 Penn Libraries call numbers: GC5 A100 523s GC5 B7539 560v Other images from this book GC5 F5948 549s 1550 All images from this book GC55 A100 593w All images from this book GC7 Sc713 733h All images from this book

photo.title: Italian lute tablature for two dances ("Romanes[ca?]" and "Gaglia[rda?]") to be played on an instrument in six courses
photo.description: Paper leaf of early (ca. 1600?) ms. music manuscript with blank verso used as binder's waste (front pastedown, detached from upper board; another leaf of music, possibly from the same ms., is used as the back pastedown, with notation visible only as bleed-through). Contents: Italian lute tablature for two dances ("Romanes[ca?]" and "Gaglia[rda?]") to be played on an instrument in six courses (g'' [above middle c'] d'' a f c G) with one diapason (F). Information supplied by Arthur Ness. He also notes that a gagliarda "is usually a fast dance in triple meter, but here in duple ... [I]t is not related [to the romanesca] since it is in a different key." "During the 16th century, Italian tablature was also used in Spain, southern France, and Bavaria ... After ca. 1600, French tablature gained international ascendancy except in Italy and Spain."--"Tablature" in The New Harvard Dictionary of Music, ed. D.M. Randel (Cambridge, Mass.: Belknap Press, 1986), p. 830. Several pieces of early parchment Latin ms. in a small and highly abbreviated glossing(?) hand used as binder's waste on spine. Penn Libraries call number: GrC Ar466 Ef54 1537 Folio All images from this book
